{"id":"2206.03026","submitter":"Yong-Jun Zhang","authors":"Nian-Qin Zhang, Yong-Jun Zhang","title":"ATP-dependent mismatch recognition in DNA replication mismatch repair","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph q-bio.BM","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Mismatch repair is a critical step of DNA replication after base selection\nand proofreading, increasing fidelity greatly, e.g., from one error per million\nbase pairs to one error per billion base pairs. The mismatch recognition\nmechanism has not been established, and most speculations are based on\nexploiting thermodynamic equilibrium and free energy. Moreover, the\ncorresponding enzyme needs to recognize not only mismatches but also correct\nmatches. The accuracy of recognizing correct matches should be very high\nbecause mistaking correct matches for mismatches would introduce extra errors\ndue to repair mistakes. Thus, non-equilibrium should play a role because it has\nthe ability to give rise to high recognition accuracy by consuming adenosine\ntriphosphate (ATP). Here we explore this possibility. Since the knowledge of\nactual MMR enzymes is incomplete, we construct a hypothetical enzyme, which is\na quantum system having three discrete energy levels. ATP raises the enzyme to\nthe highest energy level to trigger a spontaneous quantum transition, whose\nresult is one of the two low energy levels, each representing a possible\nrecognition result, i.e., a correct match or a mismatch. The ratio between the\nprobabilities of the two outcomes is exponentially proportional to the energy\ngap between the two low energy levels. The energy gap can flip to discriminate\nbetween mismatches and correct matches.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 7 Jun 2022 05:58:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Aug 2022 12:32:27 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 2 Dec 2022 10:12:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-05"}
