nce travelled. In urban areas,\nhowever, follow-up mandates also decreased distance, and the effect exceeded\nthat of initial non-compulsory measures. Stricter metre rules, gyms closing and\nreopening, restrictions on guests in homes, and face mask recommendations most\nimpacted distance travelled. Time travelled was most affected by gyms closing\nand restaurants and shops reopening.\n  Conclusion: Overall, non-compulsory measures appeared to decrease distance\ntravelled from home, while mandates further decreased this metric in urban\nareas. Time travelled is reduced more by mandates than by non-compulsory\nmeasures for all regions and interventions. Stricter distancing and restricted\nnumber of guests were associated with decreases in mobility.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Jun 2022 18:17:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-09"}
